In[72]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.stats as stats


# Pastikan data memiliki kolom 'stag' untuk waktu dan 'event' untuk data tersensor
time = data['stag']
event = data['event']

# Langkah 2: Mendefinisikan fungsi untuk membuat probability plot
def probability_plot(data, dist_name, ax):
    if dist_name == 'lognorm':
        shape, loc, scale = stats.lognorm.fit(data, floc=0)  # fit dengan floc=0 untuk lognorm
        params = (shape, loc, scale)
    else:
        dist = getattr(stats, dist_name)
        params = dist.fit(data)

    # Menggunakan distribusi yang sesuai dengan parameter yang diperoleh
    (osm, osr), (slope, intercept, r) = stats.probplot(data, dist=dist_name, sparams=params, plot=ax)
    ax.set_title(f'{dist_name.capitalize()}')
    ax.set_xlabel('Days')
    ax.set_ylabel('Percent')
    ax.grid(True)

    # Hitung kolmogorov-smirnov statistic
    ks_stat, p_value = stats.kstest(data, dist_name, args=params)
    ax.text(0.5, 0.9, f'KS Stat: {ks_stat:.2f}\n(p-value: {p_value:.2f})',
            horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='center',
            transform=ax.transAxes, bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8))

# Langkah 3: Menyiapkan plot
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

# Membuat plot untuk berbagai distribusi
distributions = ['weibull_min', 'lognorm', 'expon', 'norm']
for dist_name, ax in zip(distributions, axs.flatten()):
    probability_plot(time[event == 1], dist_name, ax)  # hanya menggunakan data yang tidak tersensor

# Menambahkan judul besar
fig.suptitle('Probability Plot for Stag', fontsize=16)

# Menampilkan plot
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])
plt.show()

The ``p_value_threshold`` is set at 0.05. Even under the null hypothesis of no violations, some
covariates will be below the threshold by chance. This is compounded when there are many covariates.
Similarly, when there are lots of observations, even minor deviances from the proportional hazard
assumption will be flagged.

With that in mind, it's best to use a combination of statistical tests and visual tests to determine
the most serious violations. Produce visual plots using ``check_assumptions(..., show_plots=True)``
and looking for non-constant lines. See link [A] below for a full example.

Survival

In[102]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from lifelines import CoxPHFitter

# Assuming data7 is already defined with columns 'stag' and 'event'

# Fit the semi-parametric Cox model
cph_semi = CoxPHFitter().fit(data9, 'stag', event_col='event')

# Fit the piecewise Cox model with breakpoints at 20 and 35
cph_piecewise = CoxPHFitter(baseline_estimation_method="piecewise", breakpoints=[20, 35]).fit(data9, 'stag', event_col='event')

# Assuming cph_spline is defined as another CoxPHFitter model (e.g., using penalized splines if available)
# Here, we'll fit another CoxPHFitter model to serve as the spline model, though lifelines may not directly support splines
# For demonstration, let's assume it is another semi-parametric fit or penalized fit
cph_spline = CoxPHFitter(penalizer=0.1).fit(data7, 'stag', event_col='event')

# Plot the baseline survival functions for each model
ax = cph_spline.baseline_survival_.plot(label="Spline-based Cox model")
cph_semi.baseline_survival_.plot(ax=ax, drawstyle="steps-post", label="Semi-parametric Cox model")
cph_piecewise.baseline_survival_.plot(ax=ax, label="Piecewise Cox model (breakpoints at 20, 35)")

# Add legend
plt.legend(["Spline", "CoxPH", "Piecewise"])

# Show the plot
plt.title("Survival Functions")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Survival Probability")
plt.show()
